This article is a statement made by the President of the United States in 2010 regarding the awarding of the Nobel Peace Prize. The President expresses humility at receiving the award and acknowledges that Mr. Liu Xiaobo is more deserving. He highlights the importance of building a just peace that upholds human rights and dignity, as outlined in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. The President mentions other Nobel Laureates who have worked towards freedom and justice, such as Aung San Suu Kyi, Jose Ramos Horta, and Desmond Tutu. He emphasizes that human rights are universal and should not be limited to any particular nation, region, or faith. While acknowledging China's accomplishments, the President believes that human dignity also requires the advancement of democracy, open society, and the rule of law. He expresses regret that Mr. Liu and his wife were denied the opportunity to attend the award ceremony and calls for the release of Mr. Liu. The President concludes by urging everyone to redouble their efforts in promoting universal values for all human beings.